Considering the [[dual space of quotient spaces|Dualraum von Quotientenvektorr√§umen]], we find that
$$
\Lambda^k V\coloneqq (\Lambda_k V)^*\subset \left(V^{\otimes k}\right)^*
$$
Is the subspace of $$k$$-linear maps $$V^k\to\R$$ that are alternating. We define the wedge product on $$\Lambda^1 V=V^*$$ to be
$$
\omega\wedge\eta\coloneqq \omega\otimes\eta-\eta\otimes\omega.
$$
More generally, for $$\omega\in\Lambda^k V$$ and $$\eta\in\Lambda^l V,$$ we define $$(\omega\wedge\eta)(v_1,\dots,v_{k+l})$$ to be
$$
\frac 1 {k!\,l!} \sum_{\sigma\in S_{k+l}}(\sign\sigma)
  \omega{\left(v_{\sigma(1)},\dots,v_{\sigma(k)}\right)}
  \eta{\left(v_{\sigma(k+1)},\dots,v_{\sigma(k+l)}\right)}.
$$
With this definition, if $$(e_i)$$ is a basis for $$V$$ and $$(\omega_i)$$ is the [[dual basis|Duale Basis]] for $$\Lambda^1 V=V^*,$$ then
$$
\left\{\omega^{i_1\cdots i_k}\coloneqq
\omega^{i_1}\wedge\dots\wedge\omega^{i_k}\right\}
$$
is the basis of $$\Lambda^k V$$ dual to the [[basis|Basis for exterior algebras]] $$(e_{i_1\cdots i_k})$$ for $$\Lambda_k V.$$ Ultimately, we get a $$2^m$$-dimensional anticommutative [[graded algebra|Graded algebra]]
$$
\Lambda^* V\coloneqq\bigoplus_{k=0}^m \Lambda^k V.
$$